            <summary>
              <p>2 fol.; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: KFQ 18; Lines per page: 10; Dimensions: 184 x 137 mm (fol. 1), 185 x 140 mm (fol. 2); Qurʾānic Text: Q 24:23-27, Q 28:6-10; Script style: kūfī D.Va; Estimated date of production: 800-1000.</p>
              <p>Cf. entry by François Déroche about fragment KFQ 18 (Déroche, <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992</ref>, p. 103): "51 / Two folios / End of the 9th century AD or first half of the 10th / 18.4x13.7cm (folio I) and 18.5x14cm (folio 2), with 10 lines to the page (11 on folio 2b) / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> Parchment; the verso is the hair side / <hi rend="italic">Text area</hi> 12.5x9.8cm / <hi rend="italic">Script</hi> Related to style D.V.A / <hi rend="italic">Accession no</hi>. KFQ18 / Like cat.44, these folios show how the evolution of Islamic book production influenced the way that Qur’ans were made. In this case, it is the format of the material that shows the impact of the changes. Only a limited number of Qur’ans in the Early Abbasid scripts were produced in the vertical format, and it appears that style D.Va was frequently associated with this format. These comments must remain largely hypothetical, however, until a larger sample of early Qur’an material has been published. / The text – <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al-nūr</hi> (XXIV), verse 23-27, and <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al-qaṣaṣ</hi> (XXVIII), verse 6-10 – is written in black ink, with diacritical strokes which were mostly added in ink or in colour. Red dots indicate the vocalization. The verses are not punctuated, but a gold Kufic <hi rend="italic">hāʾ</hi> marks the end of every fifth verse.”</p>
            </summary>
